Narrative: A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1), operating in autonomous mode, was gradually slowing to a stop for a red traffic signal on southbound [XXX] at the intersection with [XXX] in San Francisco when it was rear-ended by a passenger car (Vehicle 2) traveling directly behind. The Zoox vehicle operator then disengaged from autonomy. Both vehicles proceeded a few feet further and pulled over to exchange information. Both the Zoox vehicle and Vehicle 2 sustained minor damage. The police were not called. The Zoox vehicle operator reported back pain after the collision.

At 2:23pm:  WeRide driverless vehicle (vehicle 1) with a safety operator seated in front passenger seat, was travelling 45mph without much traffic ahead when a BMW x3 (vehicle 2) travelling in the adjacent left lane and in the same direction, merged into vehicle 1's left front quarter panel. Vehicle 1 and Vehicle 2 sustained moderate damages.
After discussing the incident with vehicle 2's driver, they admitted they were attempting to make an upcoming right turn off the expressway. They initiated 2 consecutive right lane changes abruptly before hitting vehicle 1 on their last attempted lane change.
After the initial impact, vehicle 1 was forced out of the initial lane, onto a divide, and ultimately came to a stop on the shoulder of the expressway. At this time both occupants of vehicle 1 and vehicle 2 were able to assess respective damages and exchange information. It was determined that there were no injuries. WeRide Vehicle (Vehicle 1) required a tow back to the facility.

A May autonomous shuttle (ego) was stopped at a traffic light in autonomous mode. A vehicle approaching from behind coasted into the ego vehicle. Our system responded with a software Health Drop, which immediately took the ego out of autonomous mode (for safety).
Minor damage was reported to our rear sensor and bumper.

Manual control was initiated by a May autonomous shuttle operator for a right turn onto [XXX] in Atlanta, GA.  Autonomous mode was then engaged.  The autonomous system executed a stop due to a narrow passage obstructed by parked vehicles on both sides of the roadway and an approaching vehicle.  Following the departure of the first vehicle and the next oncoming vehicle 80m away, the Autonomous Vehicle Operator (AVO) disengages and proceeds in manual.  The AVO overcorrects to the right slightly and a minor contact with the parked car's mirror occurs.  Our team looked at the incident and determined that this event was caused by human error - no autonomy software defects led to this incident.

On May [XXX], 2025, a Plus autonomous test truck was driving in autonomous mode on a public highway in Texas with a Safety Driver.  Plus's safety drivers are experienced and well-trained. The Safety Driver operating the particular vehicle has 12-years of over-the-road commercial vehicle driving experience. All safety drivers are trained to manage potential hazards they may encounter on the roads and are encouraged to retake control of the vehicle whenever necessary to ensure safe operation.  
Here, the Plus vehicle was traveling Northbound on [XXX] at approximately 63 mph in mild to moderate traffic with clear weather conditions.  According to the video camera log, the truck was in autonomous mode when a black SUV traveling in the right-most driving lane swerved to the right into the emergency lane (i.e., the shoulder) to avoid a vehicle that had stopped before it in the driving lane. Seeing the disabled vehicle in the driving lane, the Plus Safety Driver took control of the truck by applying the brakes and began to decelerate the vehicle. Two vehicles traveling behind the black SUV in the same lane then swerved to the left and into the lane in which the Plus vehicle was traveling.  The left side of the second of these vehicles (a minivan) made contact with the Plus truck's right side. [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION]
The Plus truck swerved slightly into the lane to its left as a result of the contact, avoiding a pickup truck that was passing by it. The Safety Driver then re-centered the vehicle into the truck's original lane. After the contact, the minivan moved into the rightmost lane and then ultimately came to a stop in the emergency lane.  The Plus Safety Driver changed lanes and also brought the truck to a stop in the emergency lane.
A Police report was taken at the scene, but the Plus Safety Driver did not receive a copy of it.  Based on our best information, none of the passengers in the minivan reported injuries and the only damage was to the vehicle's driver-side tire.  The minivan nevertheless was towed away from the scene.  The Plus truck did not have any damage and was able to continue driving to its destination.

An unoccupied Zoox vehicle in autonomy was stopped at a red light in the right travel lane on southbound [XXX] at the intersection with [XXX] and [XXX] in San Francisco. The Zoox vehicle cleared the intersection, then pulled over on [XXX], and shortly after was towed from the scene for inspection. The Zoox vehicle sustained minor damage to the right front body. An SUV (Vehicle 2) to the left of the Zoox vehicle, was traveling ahead in the same direction in the adjacent lane. Just as the Zoox vehicle entered the intersection, the SUV suddenly veered right across the path of the Zoox vehicle. The Zoox vehicle braked hard in response to the encroaching SUV, the Zoox vehicle operator then disengaged from autonomy, and shortly after, the front passenger side of the SUV made contact with the front driver side of the Zoox vehicle. The SUV rotated counterclockwise after impact and the rear passenger side of the SUV made contact with the rear driver side of the Zoox vehicle. The SUV sustained major damage with airbag deployment and the Zoox vehicle sustained moderate damage to the driver side. Both vehicles were towed from the scene. The police and EMS arrived at the scene. The Zoox vehicle operator reported "body soreness" and "limping" a few hours after the collision.

A May shuttle began a test shift on experimental software in a parking sub-lot. The vehicle exited the sub-lot and rolled over a curb. The vehicle stopped at a stop sign at the exit of the main lot. As it proceeded to turn onto the main road, it rolled over another curb. Almost immediately after rolling the curb, the vehicle began to drift right in lane, rubbing the vehicle sidewall on a curb. The test driver intervened immediately, but not before the sidewall of the rear right tire was weakened. Later during the drive while under manual control, the sidewall fails, eventually leading to a low pressure indicator illuminating in the dash. It was discovered that the deployment of map files, which must remain compatible, was incomplete, leaving a mismatch in the system. This resulted in the vehicle having an incorrect estimate of where lanes are in the coordinates of our localization map, and as a result, the vehicle had an incorrect estimate of proximity to lane boundaries, resulting in curb strikes.

While traveling northbound on[XXX] in Martinez, a car pulled out of a driveway on the right side without right of way and collided with the right side of May's vehicle (t-bone.)
May's vehicle was traveling at approximately 20 MPH in a residential neighborhood, and was approximately 1m left of lane center when a black vehicle exited a driveway on the right from behind a fence, facing the road and May's vehicle. This vehicle did not slow down or stop until entering into the roadway and collided with the May vehicle's right side. AVO attempts to swerve to the left but is unable to avoid a collision. 
The primary factor that led to the collision was the other vehicles action proceeding without the right-of-way into the side of the May vehicle. Upon further inspection, it was determined that we did not predict this collision until it was too late to avoid it even by veering. The velocity of the other vehicle was underestimated and was largely given only yield policies as having the most significant likelihood. There is some room for improvement in our response, which we plan to implement in future software releases, namely, an emergency veer policy must exist that is capable of moving quickly and far enough to possibly avoid the collision, more accurate reporting of velocity for slow-moving agents, estimate acceleration when assessing risk, improvements to predictions of the probability of an agent yielding, and adjusting our risk assessment so that it is heading dependent and more risk would be associated with passing close in front of another vehicle.

A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1) in autonomous mode was traveling in the right lane on southbound [XXX] approaching [XXX] in Paradise, NV. The Zoox vehicle operator disengaged from autonomy and drove over an in-lane, dislodged manhole cover with the front passenger side tire of the vehicle, causing the manhole cover to rise and strike the passenger side rear wheel and tire. The impact debeaded the tire and fractured the wheel rim. The Zoox vehicle then rotated clockwise, towards the concrete planter on the right side abutting the curb. The Zoox vehicle operator then braked and the front end of the Zoox vehicle made contact with the concrete planter. Besides damage to the passenger side wheel and rim, the Zoox vehicle's front end also sustained damage. The police were called to the scene and there were no reported injuries.

On December [XXX], 2024 at 8:28 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Los Angeles, CA was in a collision involving two SUV's, a passenger car, and a pick up truck on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was stopped in autonomous mode facing south at a red light as the lead vehicle in the second from the right lane when an SUV traveling northbound in an oncoming traffic lane ran the red light.  As the oncoming SUV entered the intersection, it made contact with a passenger car traveling east on [XXX].  The oncoming SUV continued through the intersection and swerved to narrowly miss a pedestrian before making contact with the front of the Waymo AV and the front driver side of a stationary pickup truck to the right of the Waymo AV.  The impact from the oncoming SUV caused the Waymo AV to contact another SUV that was also stationary to the left of the Wayo AV at the red traffic light.  The Waymo AV test driver transitioned to manual mode immediately before the oncoming SUV made contact.  At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was not engaged and a test driver was operating the Waymo AV in manual mode.  The Waymo AV sustained damage to the front and rear of the vehicle, necessitating a tow from the scene.  The oncoming SUV sustained damage to the front and driver side.  The stationary SUV that was contacted sustained damage to the passenger side.  The Waymo test driver was transported to a local hospital for medical treatment.
Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this crash under Request no. 1 of Standing General order 2021-01 because an individual involved was transported from the scene to a hospital for medical treatment, a vehicle involved was towed away, and because of airbag deployment.  Transdev may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.  This is a duplicate of NHTSA Report ID: 30270-9476-2.

On November [XXX], 2024 at 7:23PM CST, a Cruise autonomous vehicle ("AV") operating in supervised autonomous mode in Houston, Texas was traveling west on [XXX] when it decelerated as it approached a speed bump. As the AV began to slowly traverse the speed bump, it maneuvered slightly left to provide room for a cyclist approaching from behind the AV on the right-hand side. As the cyclist approached quickly from behind the AV, they moved from the right side of the road to the left side and attempted to maneuver around the AV, between the AV and a parked vehicle. The cyclist then lost control of their bike while maneuvering the speed bump and fell to the ground in front of and to the left of the AV. The AV came to a complete stop and the Cruise safety driver took manual control of the AV, remaining stationary. The cyclist proceeded to get to their feet and spoke with the safety driver, but did not report any injuries when asked. There was no indication of property damage to the AV.

A Zoox vehicle in autonomous mode was stopped for a red traffic light on northbound [XXX] while preparing to turn left onto westbound [XXX] in San Francisco. After the light turned green the Zoox vehicle began to move forward and then slowed gradually to yield to a pedestrian with right of way in the crosswalk on [XXX]. On October [XXX], 2024 at 3:58 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a passenger car on [XXX] at [XXX].

As the Waymo AV approached the intersection and came to a stop, a passenger car which was following behind the Waymo AV at a low rate of speed approached the Waymo AV from behind and partially crossed into the right-hand travel lane. A May autonomous vehicle was traveling in the right lane of a two-lane road, maintaining a steady speed of 30 mph, in compliance with the posted speed limit. The road was characterized by light traffic, with a slight curvature that transitioned from a gentle rightward sway to a leftward sway. As the vehicle navigated this transition of curvature, the May vehicle made contact with the curb, causing a flat tire. 
At the time of the incident, no other vehicles or pedestrians were present in the immediate vicinity, and there were no external factors such as obstructions or adverse weather conditions influencing the vehicles path.
Speed was reduced from 30mph to 25mph after this event and tested (and worked to mitigate the problem in that area) and now will be reduced to 22 which is the sweet spot for most areas on the route. The May vehicle chose to maneuver at the curb due to perceived risk from a car in an adjacent lane, so May is increasing the allowed distance to the curb to mitigate how close the vehicles are allowed to get.

A Motional AV with VIN PFDKB4AE6RF[XXX] was operating in autonomous mode in Las Vegas, Nevada at approximately 1 PM PT, with a safety driver at the wheel, an engineer in the front passenger seat, and two other employees in the rear seats.

A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1) in autonomy was gradually slowing to a stop in the right travel lane (lane 5) for a red traffic signal on southbound [XXX] at the intersection with [XXX] in Spring Valley, Nevada. A motorcyclist (Vehicle 2), also southbound on [XXX], was traveling at high speed in the left through lane (lane 3), aggressively approaching a slowing SUV (Vehicle 3) in lane 3. The motorcyclist clipped the right rear corner of Vehicle 3, deflecting the motorcycle to the right, causing the motorcyclist to lose control and fall to the pavement. The motorcyclist was sliding on the pavement when the motorcycle made contact with the Zoox vehicle's rear bumper. The Zoox vehicle operator disengaged from autonomy and brought the vehicle to a stop. The motorcycle came to rest on its right side with the motorcyclist's right leg stuck underneath the motorcycle. An adjacent bystander immediately aided the motorcyclist and asked the Zoox vehicle operator to move the Zoox vehicle "slightly forward". After the Zoox operator moved the vehicle forward, the bystander lifted the motorcycle and the motorcyclist remained on the ground for a short period of time before standing up and walking around the scene. The motorcyclist was observed to have injuries. Police and EMS were called to the scene and the motorcyclist was later transported by an ambulance. The content of this report is unchanged from the initial report and provides complete information to date for this incident.

Narrative: The subject vehicle (autonomous vehicle - AV) was stopped at a red traffic light, in a queue of vehicles, heading west on [XXX], with autonomous driving (AD) mode engaged. Once the light turned green, the queue of vehicles started to move forward, the AV started to move forward with the queue, and prior to crossing the intersection, the AV was struck from behind by an SUV. After impact the safety driver of the AV applied the brakes to disengage AD mode and then proceeded to find a safe spot to assess the incident by turning right onto [XXX]. The driver of the SUV followed the AV to a safe location to assess the incident and exchange contact information. There were no reported injuries, airbag deployments, or tow-aways between either party involved.  The AV sustained minor damage to the rear of the vehicle including the rear bumper cover, rear bumper carrier, and a rear facing camera. The SUV damage was reported as scratches and dents to the front bumper cover. Both vehicles were able to safely drive away from the scene. VWGoA does not plan to investigate the incident any further as the facts and circumstances do not indicate any issue with the vehicle's performance.

Narrative:
**1-Day Incident Report 5/25/2024**
Customer contacted Kia Customer Care (KCC) to report an incident involving his 2023MY Kia Sportage. Specifically, the customer called to thank Kia "for saving [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION] life." Customer explained he was in a head-on collision when a drunk driver suddenly veered into his lane.  Customer reported he suffered "cuts, bumps & bruises" and stated he "believes that [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION] lack of injuries is due to the plethora of safety features my Sportage had."  KCC subsequently contacted the customer to obtain additional details regarding the incident.  Customer stated that he was driving on a two-lane highway around 3AM, with cruise control engaged, when the car he was following veered into a ditch and a drunk driver veered into his lane. Customer did not see the drunk driver until the last second and as a result did not have time react.  When asked by KCC, the customer responded that Highway Driving Assist (HDA) was not engaged, but that his Smart Cruise Control and Lane Following Assist were engaged at the time of the incident.  The customer reported that the Sportage's airbags deployed, both the customer and driver of the other vehicle (unclear if the drunk driver or the driver of the vehicle that veered into the ditch) were transported to the hospital and that the Sportage was towed. Customer stated he was not asking anything from Kia and that he had called only to share his appreciation. 
This incident is being reported as precautionary measure since the incident meets the requirements under the SGO.  However, based on the description of the incident provided by the customer, the incident was not caused by a failure and/or disengagement of smart cruise control and/or LFA.
**10-Day Update 6/3/2024**
No additional information to be provided as the 1-Day was reported as a precautionary measure and submitting this 10-Day Update per the reporting requirements under the SGO.

On May [XXX], 2024 at 10:37 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a pickup truck on [XXX] near [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was traveling southwest on [XXX] in the far left lane and stopped in a queue of traffic at a red light at the intersection with [XXX].  After the light turned green, the Waymo AV began to slowly move ahead while continuing to yield to the traffic ahead when the front of the pickup truck following behind the Waymo AV made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV.  At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. Both vehicles sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vehicle involved was towed away. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

ADAS/ADS System Version: SMART CRUISE CONTROL & LANE FOLLOWING ASSIST
ADAS/ADS Hardware Version: DUE TO MULTIPLE COMPONENTS, NO VERSION CAN BE PROVIDED
ADAS/ADS Software Version: DUE TO MULTIPLE COMPONENTS, NO VERSION CAN BE PROVIDED
Narrative:
Customer contacted Kia Customer Care (KCC) to report an incident involving his 2023MY Kia Sportage. Specifically, the called to thank Kia for saving [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION] life. Customer explained he was in a head-on collision when a drunk driver suddenly veered into his lane.  Customer reported he suffered cuts, bumps & bruises and stated he believes that [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION] lack of injuries is due to the plethora of safety features my Sportage had.   KCC subsequently contacted the customer to obtain additional details regarding the incident.  Customer stated that he was driving on a two-lane highway around 3AM, with cruise control engaged, when the car he was following veered into a ditch and a drunk driver veered into his lane. Customer did not see the drunk driver until the last second and as a result did not have time react.  When asked by KCC, the customer responded that Highway Driving Assist (HDA) was not engaged, but that his Smart Cruise Control and Lane Following Assist were engaged at the time of the incident.  The customer reported that the Sportages airbags deployed, both the customer and driver of the other vehicle (unclear if the drunk driver or the driver of the vehicle that veered into the ditch) were transported to the hospital and that the Sportage was towed. Customer stated he was not asking anything from Kia and that he had called only to share his appreciation. 
This incident is being reported as precautionary measure since the incident meets the requirements under the SGO.  However, based on the description of the incident provided by the customer, the incident was not caused by a failure and/or disengagement of smart cruise control and/or LFA.

On Wednesday, May [XXX], 2024 at approximately 3:45pm PST, a Nuro Prius operating in manual mode bumped a pedestrian at the intersection of [XXX] and [XXX] in Palo Alto, California.

The May vehicle was traveling through an intersection with a van in the oncoming left turn lane. As the May vehicle enters the intersection, the van creeps towards its turn.  Predicting that the two will get too close, the May vehicle elects to stop hard. As vehicle is coming to a stop in the stop-hard policy, the turning van fails to respond in time and collides with the rear left corner of the vehicle.
In the new software, deploying within the next month, agent-proximity has been replaced with agent-clearance. Performing resimulations of the incident with the latest branch verifies that this issue does not persist.

A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1) in autonomy was stopped at a red light in the right travel lane on southbound [XXX] at the intersection with [XXX]/[XXX] in San Francisco. After the light turned green, the Zoox vehicle entered the intersection and began bearing right onto southbound [XXX] when a lane-splitting motorcycle (Vehicle 2) operator maneuvered around other traffic and quickly came up on the rear of the Zoox vehicle, traversing laterally in lane from the left to the right side of the Zoox vehicle. On February [XXX], 2024 at 2:34 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a bicyclist on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling westbound on [XXX] and came to a stop at a 4-way stop sign intersection at [XXX]. When it was the Waymo AVs turn at the intersection, the Waymo AV entered the intersection to proceed straight. At this point, a delivery truck traveling eastbound on [XXX] was already in the middle of the intersection (the delivery truck arrived at its stop sign first and proceeded into the intersection before the Waymo AV). As the Waymo AV passed the rear of the delivery truck, an occluded bicyclist who was traveling behind the delivery truck became visible and was making a sharp left turn onto northbound [XXX], in front of the Waymo AVs path. The cyclist had entered the 4-way stop intersection without stopping or yielding. The Waymo AV detected the bicyclist, applied heavy braking, but was unable to avoid contact with the bicyclist before coming to a full stop. 
At the time of the impact, the Waymo AVs Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained minor body damage, and the bicyclist reported minor injuries and damage to their bicycle. The Waymo AV remained stopped in the intersection for approximately one minute, and after the path was clear, resumed driving for a short period of time. The Waymo AV was then returned to the scene by one of Waymos roadside assistance specialists. The Waymo AV did not require towing and was returned to the depot in manual mode.

A Ghost ADS-equipped car was driving engaged Northbound on [XXX]. As always, there were two safety drivers in the car. Traffic was moving in all four lanes at or near the speed limit. The Ghost vehicle was in the right-middle lane. Another vehicle (the "lead" car) entered into the Ghost car's lane from the right. While there were numerous vehicles ahead of the Ghost car before that vehicle entered the lane, the lead vehicle blocked the view of the lane before it. Throughout the incident, traffic in the other three lanes continued at a steady pace.
When the lead vehicle entered into the lane ahead of the Ghost car, the Ghost car applied the brakes to accommodate the intrusion and then continued to match the speed of the lead car. The lead car suddenly slammed the brakes. The Ghost car followed suit, reducing its speed from 19 mps (42.5 mph) to 4.7 mps (10.5 mph) within the next three seconds. The Ghost car was able to match the rapid speed reduction of the lead car and avoid contact.
The driver following the Ghost car was not able to respond as quickly as the Ghost ADS. When the following driver began to apply the brakes, the car was about five meters behind and was traveling at 6.5 mps. At the point of impact, the Ghost vehicle was traveling at 4.78 mps (10.7 mph), matching the lead car. There were no injuries. The vehicles suffered only cosmetic damage, the drivers exchanged information, and the Ghost safety drivers returned to home base in conventional mode.

Cruise is submitting this updated report to indicate in the Post-Crash Information section that it has received a California Highway Patrol Traffic Collision Report in connection with the reported incident.  There are no other changes to Cruise's previous submission (30412-6395-3): A Cruise autonomous vehicle (AV), operating in driverless autonomous mode, was at a complete stop in response to a red light on southbound [XXX] at the intersection with [XXX]. A dark colored Nissan Sentra was also stopped in the adjacent lane to the left of the AV. As the Nissan Sentra and the AV proceeded through the intersection after the light turned green, a pedestrian entered the crosswalk on the opposite side of [XXX] across from the vehicles and proceeded through the intersection against a red light. The pedestrian passed completely through the AVs lane of travel but stopped mid-crosswalk in front of the Nissan Sentra. Shortly thereafter, the Nissan Sentra made contact with the pedestrian, deflecting the pedestrian in front of the AV. The AV braked aggressively but, shortly thereafter, made contact with the pedestrian. The AV then attempted to pull over out of traffic, pulling the individual forward, rather than remaining stationary. The driver of the Nissan Sentra left the scene shortly after the collision. Police and Emergency Medical Services (EMS) were called to the scene and the pedestrian was transported by EMS. On November 2, 2023, Cruise submitted a voluntary recall report to NHTSA relating to the AVs response after the collision, based on updated analysis that Cruise performed since the filing of the previous submissions.

A Cruise autonomous vehicle (AV), operating in driverless autonomous mode, was at a complete stop in response to a red light on southbound [XXX] at the intersection with [XXX]. A dark colored Nissan Sentra was also stopped in the adjacent lane to the left of the AV. As the Nissan Sentra and the AV proceeded through the intersection after the light turned green, a pedestrian entered the crosswalk on the opposite side of [XXX] across from the vehicles and proceeded through the intersection against a red light. The pedestrian passed completely through the AVs lane of travel but stopped mid-crosswalk in front of the Nissan Sentra. Shortly thereafter, the Nissan Sentra made contact with the pedestrian, deflecting the pedestrian in front of the AV. The AV braked aggressively but, shortly thereafter, made contact with the pedestrian. The AV then attempted to pull over out of traffic, pulling the individual forward, rather than remaining stationary. The driver of the Nissan Sentra left the scene shortly after the collision. Police and Emergency Medical Services (EMS) were called to the scene and the pedestrian was transported by EMS. On November 2, 2023, Cruise submitted a voluntary recall report to NHTSA relating to the AVs response after the collision, based on updated analysis that Cruise performed since the filing of the previous submissions. The AV safety driver disengaged from autonomous mode and attempted to dodge the debris. However, the debris made contact with the rear bumper, slightly damaging it. Following the collision, the AV safety driver promptly drove the AV to Pony.ai's Fremont facility. There were no injuries reported.

Narrative:
At Approximately 12:39 PM, the Beep Command Center (BCC) informed the LYNX dispatch center that another autonomous shuttle operating on the same route (VIN: VG9A2CB2CJV[XXX]) was being taken out of service due to insufficient battery charge to continue operation. The BCC later informed LYNX dispatch at 12:49PM that the second shuttle operating on route, P131, would also be returning to storage after the operator completed its current loop. At Approximately 12:52 PM, P131 approached the [XXX] stop within the designated Bus Rapid Transit (BRT) operating lane. The shuttle remained stopped for approximately two (2) and a half minutes while three (3) passengers alighted, and two (2) additional passengers boarded the shuttle. During that period, approximately two (2) minutes after stopping to service passengers, a LYNX bus pulled behind P131. Approximately thirty (30) seconds later, the LYNX bus exited the BRT lane and proceeded into the public travel lane alongside the BRT lane. As the LYNX bus entered the public travel lane, the safety driver onboard P131 engaged the autonomous drive system, and the shuttle proceeded in the BRT lane. After both vehicles had begun moving, P131 in the BRT lane and the LYNX bus in the public travel lane, the LYNX bus reentered the BRT lane encroaching on the shuttles path. The bus failed to provide adequate clearance and contacted the left front side of P131. Both vehicles stopped in the BRT lane after the collision. 
Within five (5) minutes of the collision, all passengers had safely alighted from the shuttle with no reported injuries and left the scene without giving statements. At approximately 2:20PM, the City of Orlando Police Department (OPD) arrived on scene to investigate the incident. Beep and LYNX supervisors were on scene to support the investigation. OPD collected statements from both the Beep safety driver and LYNX bus driver. The LYNX supervisor provided OPD access to the LYNX bus camera footage on scene, at which point the investigating officer made a verbal indication that the LYNX bus driver appeared to be at fault for the collision. 
Beeps safety driver was subsequently subjected to a standard post-collision drug and alcohol screening. 
1.The safety driver did not exhibit complete situational awareness and per their after-incident interview, failed to notice the bus prior to departing the station. Had the attendant continued to look and check behind/alongside P131 prior to departing the station,
the collision may have been avoided.
2.The safety driver attempted to stop the shuttle by disengaging the ADS using the HMI rather than using the emergency stop button. Use of the emergency stop would have increased the deceleration rate to 5 m/s2, decreasing the stopping distance of the shuttle. However, it is not clear whether use of the emergency stop would have fully avoided the collision given the point at which the LYNX LYMMO bus entered the BRT lane.
3.Deficiencies in the standard operating procedures (SOP) between LYNX and Beep allowed for a bus to be deployed onto the service at the same time as P131. Beep communicated to LYNX that both shuttles were exiting the service area. However, LYNX did not wait for final confirmation that both vehicles had left the route prior to dispatching the LYMMO bus involved in the incident, nor did LYNX notify Beep that a bus had been dispatched.
Additional information available upon request.

Narrative:
VIN # VG9A2CB2CIV[XXX] 
At approximately 5:54 p.m. on Wednesday, August [XXX], 2023, P84, travelling eastbound on [XXX], approached the three-way stop at [XXX] and [XXX]. P84 arrived at the intersection at the same time as two other vehicles: a grey van heading northbound on [XXX] and a red sedan heading westbound on [XXX]. The safety driver yielded to the northbound vehicle, which proceeded to make a right-hand turn eastbound onto [XXX]. After allowing the intersection to clear, the safety driver onboard P84 confirmed that it was safe for the shuttle to proceed through the intersection. As the shuttle entered the intersection, a second vehicle travelling northbound on [XXX], a white sedan, entered the intersection intending a left-hand turn onto westbound [XXX]. Both vehicles entered the intersection simultaneously, subsequently colliding at a low rate of speed in the middle of the intersection.  
At approximately 5:57 p.m., the Beep Command Center (BCC) was informed by the safety driver that P84 was involved in a minor collision with another vehicle at the intersection of [XXX] and [XXX]. The incident response protocol was initiated, and a supervisor dispatched to the scene. Local law enforcement (San Francisco Police Department) was contacted to report the collision but declined to respond given the minor nature of the collision, directing both parties to exchange information. After the Beep supervisor arrived on scene at approximately 6:49 p.m., the safety driver and supervisor removed the shuttle from the roadway and exchanged insurance information with the driver of the other vehicle. 
Damage to both vehicles was noted to be very minor. The shuttle sustained light scuffs, chips, and small paint transfer. The other vehicle sustained a small dent on the fender. Neither vehicle required towing, and both were safely driven from the scene. 
Beeps safety driver was subsequently subjected to a standard post-collision drug & alcohol screening which has since cleared.  
Contributing Factors 
Based on an analysis of the available evidence, Beep has determined the following factors may have contributed to the higher likelihood of a collision occurring in this instance: 
1.The white sedan failed to yield to P84 in accordance with California state law governing intersection priority.
2.The slight bend in P84s path to accommodate the lane shift through the intersection may have reduced the available stopping distance as the white sedan was not perceived as an obstacle in P84s path until it proceeded further into the intersection.
Incident Findings 
Beep developed the following findings regarding this incident:
1.P84 behaved as expected, detecting and maintaining awareness of the white sedan in the moments preceding the collision, commanding hard braking maneuver, and achieving a 3m/s2 deceleration rate once the white sedan encroached on P84s path.
2.The safety driver observed California state law and had the right of way when releasing P84 into the intersection.
3.The safety driver could have avoided the collision by using the emergency stop. The safety driver indicated that they were aware of the other vehicle through the duration of the incident and were aware of the proper procedure in this scenario but panicked in the moment.
Mitigation:
Implement a priority zone to account for the slight bend in the shuttles path and for future vehicles that may fail to yield.

On August [XXX], 2023 at 9:54 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a heavy truck on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling northbound on [XXX] when it approached a heavy truck and trailer that was stopped in the adjacent lane on the left side of the street. As the Waymo began to slowly pass the truck, the truck initiated a reversing turn maneuver into a loading bay on the left side of [XXX]. The Waymo AV then came to a stop, and as the Waymo AV was initiating its own reversing maneuver to clear the path for the truck, the right side of the trailer made contact with the front driver's side corner of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On August [XXX], 2023 at 5:49 PM PT the mirror of a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, CA was struck by a cyclist on [XXX]. Drive at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was stopped in traffic on eastbound [XXX] Drive at the intersection with [XXX], when a cyclist that had been traveling behind the Waymo AV passed the Waymo AV on the left. As the cyclist passed the Waymo AV, the cyclist made contact with the driver side mirror of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present (in the driver's seating position). The Waymo AV sustained damage and the cyclist did not stop, leaving the scene without exchanging information.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On August [XXX], 2023 at 4:45 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a passenger car on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV entered the slip lane which connects westbound [XXX] to northbound [XXX] and came to a stop to yield to cross-traffic on [XXX]. As the Waymo AV was stopped, the front of the passenger car which was traveling behind the Waymo AV made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present (in the driver's seating position). The Waymo AV sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On August [XXX], 2023 at 1:05 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving an SUV on [XXX] near [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling northbound on [XXX]. As the SUV was passing the Waymo AV to the left, it initiated a right lane change. The front of the SUV made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. Both vehicles sustained damage, and the SUV left the scene without exchanging information.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On August [XXX], 2023, Waymo received notice of an allegation that a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV")  contributed to a low-speed collision between a fire engine and an SUV on [XXX] at [XXX].
On August [XXX], 2023 at 6:11 PM PT, a Waymo AV operating in San Francisco, California was stopped at a red light in the dedicated left turn lane on the left side of northeast-bound [XXX] at the intersection with [XXX]. While the light was red, a fire engine approached the Waymo AV from behind and the Waymo AV moved forward as far as possible before entering the intersection at [XXX]. After the light turned green and as the Waymo AV was calculating a path into the intersection to clear the way, the fire engine maneuvered around the Waymo AV on the right side. During this maneuver, the right side of the fire engine appears to have made contact with the front left corner of an SUV that was stopped in the through lane to the right of the Waymo AV. The fire engine then proceeded through the intersection, and shortly afterwards, another fire engine and a fire department SUV passed on the left side the Waymo AV of the stopped Waymo AV. The Waymo AV then proceeded through the intersection.
At the time of the collision, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The SUV sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On August [XXX], 2023 at 9:01 PM a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a passenger car on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling southwestbound on [XXX] in the second lane from the left as it was approaching [XXX]. As the Waymo AV was proceeding straight through the intersection, the passenger car in the right adjacent lane made a left turn from a straight-only lane onto southeastbound [XXX]. The rear of the passenger car made contact with the front of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was not engaged and a test driver was operating the Waymo AV in manual mode. Both the Waymo AV and the passenger car sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On August [XXX], 2023 at 7:38 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Los Angeles, California was in a collision involving a recycling bin on [XXX] at [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was pulling over to the right side of the road, when the test driver transitioned to manual mode and made contact with a recycling bin on the right side of the street. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was not engaged and a test driver was operating the Waymo AV in manual mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage. 
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On August [XXX], 2023 at 7:23 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Phoenix, Arizona was in a collision involving an SUV on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling north on [XXX] through the intersection with [XXX]. An SUV traveling West on [XXX] entered the intersection without stopping at the two-way stop sign on [XXX]. The Waymo AV slowed to a stop in the intersection and the front left corner of the SUV made contact with the front right corner of the Waymo AV. 
At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage. 
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On August [XXX], 2023 at 3:36 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Mesa, Arizona was in a collision involving a pickup truck on [XXX] at [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was stationary adjacent to the curb on the West side of [XXX]. A pickup truck approached the Waymo from behind and slowed to a stop immediately behind the Waymo. The pickup truck then moved slowly forward until the front of the pickup truck was touching the rear of the Waymo AV. The pickup truck then slowly pushed into the rear of the Waymo AV for a few seconds before reversing, maneuvering around the Waymo AV, and leaving the scene. 
At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage. 
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On August [XXX], 2023 at 10:09 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving an SUV on [XXX] at [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was stopped at a red light on eastbound [XXX] at [XXX]. Shortly after the traffic light turned green and the Waymo AV began to proceed forward, the Waymo AV slowed to a stop. The SUV that was traveling closely behind the Waymo AV made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. Both vehicles sustained damage, and the trailing SUV left the scene without exchanging information. A passenger in the Waymo AV reported injuries. 
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On August [XXX], 2023 at 7:12 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo") operating in Phoenix, Arizona was in a collision involving a passenger car on [XXX] at [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was stationary adjacent to the curb on the south side of [XXX]. A passenger car which had been parked in front of the Waymo AV began reversing and the rear of the passenger car made contact with the front of the Waymo AV. The passenger car then left the scene. At the time of the impact, the Waymo's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On September 14, 2023, GM Cruise Holdings LLC ("Cruise") filed an Incident Report (the "Report") under the Second Amended Standing General Order 2021-01, dated April 5, 2023 (the "Order") General Motors LLC (GM) manufactured the Cruise-operated motor vehicle involved in the incident summarized in the Incident Report. Because GM is also a Reporting Entity under the Order, GM is submitting a duplicate of the redacted public copy of the Report. GM has selected "Unknown" in the "ADS version" and "ODD time" fields solely to avoid a second submission of nonpublic Cruise CBI GM is in possession of Cruise's responses to these fields, and incorporates Cruise's responses into this submission by reference. GM's submission is based on facts supplied to GM by Cruise. GM has not investigated the alleged incident and currently believes, based on a reasonable inquiry, that it has no independent knowledge of the facts in the Report. (Reference file: 30412-6281-1)

At the same time, a large truck pulling a trailer traveling northbound on [XXX] was making an illegal U-turn inside the intersection. As the AV proceeded straight after the light turned green, the end of the large truck's trailer had not fully cleared the AV's lane of travel and made contact with the AV, damaging the AV's front bumper fascia, front camera, front grille assembly and front passenger side headlamp. A Ghost autonomous vehicle was hit by crash debris while traveling on [XXX].  The Ghost vehicle neither hit nor was hit by another vehicle.  The Ghost car was traveling in AV mode with two safety drivers.  Traffic slowed quickly, apparently due to a crash ahead of the Ghost car.  Consistent with their training, the Ghost driver took control of the car by manually braking and disengaging the autonomous system.  The car was traveling 55.3 mph when the driver began to brake.  The Ghost car stopped without impacting the preceding car.  A Mercedes car immediately following the Ghost car also came to a stop without impacting the Ghost car.  Ghost's understanding based on communications at the scene is that a Grand Cherokee traveling behind the Mercedes tried to swerve to avoid impacting the Mercedes but clipped the Mercedes and rolled over.  To Ghost's knowledge, nobody in the Grand Cherokee was injured.  The Ghost drivers heard a noise and then found that the rear bumper of the Ghost car had been damaged, which Ghost believes resulted from crash debris. The Ghost drivers drove the Ghost car back to the garage in conventional mode.

On July [XXX], 2023 at 3:34 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in Tempe, Arizona was in a collision involving a passenger vehicle on [XXX] near [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was traveling westbound on [XXX] in the left lane with a vehicle overtaking it in the right adjacent lane when it detected a large, fallen tree branch in part of its lane and applied braking in response. As the Waymo AV was braking and had slowed to 3 mph, a passenger vehicle behind the Waymo made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV. Moments later, an SUV behind the passenger vehicle made contact with the rear of the passenger vehicle. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AVs Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. All vehicles sustained damage. Rather than wearing the seat belt, the passenger in the Waymo AV was sitting on the buckled seat belt at the time of the collision. The passenger declined medical attention.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On June 23, 2023, Motional informed HMNA's NASO of a crash incident occurring on June [XXX], 2023, at 9:42 PM PDT, involving a Hyundai IONIQ 5 test vehicle operating in proprietary ADS autonomous mode with a safety driver at the wheel and a safety operator in the front passenger seat. After submitting the previous 1-Day report on [XXX], 2023 [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION], Waymo received notice that the test driver was not transported from the scene to the hospital for medical treatment, but did seek medical treatment at a hospital at a later time. As such, this event could have qualified for a 5-Day report. The narrative below has been updated to reflect this information. This updated report also now lists the Highest Injury Severity Alleged as moderate, and Transdev Alternative Services as an entity that may be aware of this incident.
On [XXX], 2023 at 1:17 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in Phoenix, AZ was in a collision involving a passenger car on [XXX] in the southbound direction near the [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling in the rightmost lane (out of 5 lanes) in the southbound direction of [XXX],  and the left 3 lanes were closed due to a work zone. The vehicle traveling ahead in the same lane as the ADV made an abrupt lane change to the left, revealing a stack of slow-moving vehicles in the Waymo AVs lane. The test driver of the Waymo AV took manual control of the vehicle and started to decelerate and steer toward the right shoulder in response to slow traffic ahead. A passenger vehicle approached the Waymo AV from behind and made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AVs Level 4 ADS was not engaged and a test driver (in the drivers seating position) was operating the Waymo AV in manual mode. The Waymo AV and the other vehicle sustained damage. The test driver reported an injury, for which they later sought medical treatment. 
Waymo reported this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On May [XXX], 2023 at 3:27 PM PDT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a cyclist on [XXX] near [XXX].

On Monday May [XXX] at 11:41am a Weride autonomous vehicle (Vehicle 1) was in Autonomous Mode stopped at the intersection of [XXX] towards [XXX] appropriately yielding to a illegally U turning skateboard on [XXX] North to South direction in front of the AV (Vehicle 1). On May [XXX], 2023 at 3:27 PM PDT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a cyclist on [XXX] near [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was traveling westbound in the left lane on [XXX] and had just passed [XXX] when it detected an oncoming pickup truck traveling eastbound in the Waymo AVs lane. The Waymo AV stopped and the pickup truck re-entered the correct lane for eastbound traffic and passed the Waymo AV. The pickup truck was immediately followed by a large group of cyclists traveling eastbound in multiple lanes of the roadway, including the right lanes and on the wrong side of the double-yellow centerline. The Waymo AV remained stopped as the oncoming cyclists rode around both sides of the Waymo AV. One cyclist then made contact with the front of the stationary Waymo AV, and then immediately left the scene. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AVs Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vulnerable road user was involved. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On Friday April [XXX] at 16:16 local time, the May shuttle was driving Westbound on [XXX] in Ann Arbor, MI in autonomous mode and was followed by another vehicle. The following vehicle was traveling approximately twice as fast as the May shuttle and catching up to the May shuttle from behind. The May shuttle began to slow for traffic ahead, which was stopping for a red light, but the following vehicle did not decelerate. While slowing, the May shuttle identified a bollard on the side of the road as a likely pedestrian and added a safety buffer which intersected with the predicted trajectory of the shuttle. This caused the shuttle to increase deceleration to avoid the projected collision with the buffer. The following vehicle started braking late and impacted the May shuttle from behind with a relative velocity of 6.2 m/s. Re-simulation of this event with a future software version shows that the May shuttle would have decelerated less abruptly.

A Zoox vehicle in autonomy had made a right turn from [XXX] onto [XXX] in Menlo Park, CA and was preparing to make an immediate, unprotected left turn onto [XXX]. A Zoox vehicle in autonomy was proceeding northbound on [XXX] in stop-and-go traffic through an active construction zone. At the same time, an e-scooter traveling near the right curb was passing other slow traffic behind the Zoox vehicle. Before the e-scooter could also pass the Zoox vehicle on the right, the e-scooter weaved away from the curb, seemingly to avoid a drainage grate, and came within a close following distance behind the Zoox vehicle. As the Zoox vehicle came to a stop again for traffic ahead the e-scooter rider did not stop, and the e-scooter made contact with the right rear tail light of the Zoox vehicle. The e-scooter rider remained upright, did not stop to exchange information, and immediately rode off while the Zoox vehicle was still stopped. There were no injuries and police were not called. The damage to the Zoox vehicle was limited to a cracked tail light lens. This 10-Day update provides complete information for this incident.

On April [XXX], 2023 at 10:46 AM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a passenger car on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling southbound on [XXX] in the leftmost lane as it was approaching the intersection with [XXX].  The signal for traffic proceeding south on [XXX] was green for the Waymo AV as it approached the intersection.  As the Waymo AV approached, an individual riding a motorized scooter traveling north on [XXX] proceeded to turn left onto westbound [XXX], across the paths of the Waymo AV and other oncoming vehicles.  The Waymo AV began to brake, and the Waymo AV test driver transitioned to manual mode and brought the Waymo AV to a stop.  A passenger car traveling directly behind the Waymo AV then made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV.  The individual riding the scooter was not contacted by the Waymo AV or any other vehicle.  At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was not engaged and a test driver was operating the Waymo AV in manual mode.  Both the Waymo AV and the passenger car sustained damage, and the individual on the motorized scooter left the scene.
Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this crash under Request No 1 of Standing General Order 2021 01 because a Vulnerable Road User was involved.  Transdev may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.  This is a duplicate of report ID 30531-5088-1.

A Cruise autonomous vehicle ("Cruise AV 1"), operating in driverless autonomous mode, was stopped for a passenger drop-off beside the right curb of [XXX] between [XXX] and [XXX]. One of the passengers of Cruise AV 1 opened the driver side rear passenger door into the lane of traffic as another Cruise AV ("Cruise AV 2"), operating in driverless autonomous mode, was passing by Cruise AV 1 in the lane of traffic on [XXX]. The door of the Cruise AV 1 made contact with Cruise AV 2 as Cruise AV 2 was passing. The contact caused damage to the left rear door of Cruise AV 1 and to the front passenger side mirror, front passenger side sensor, front passenger side fender, and front and rear passenger side door of Cruise AV 2. A Zoox vehicle in autonomy was proceeding northbound on [XXX] in stop-and-go traffic through an active construction zone. At the same time, an e-scooter traveling near the right curb was passing other slow traffic behind the Zoox vehicle. Before the e-scooter could also pass the Zoox vehicle on the right, the e-scooter weaved away from the curb, seemingly to avoid a drainage grate, and came within a close following distance behind the Zoox vehicle. As the Zoox vehicle came to a stop again for traffic ahead the e-scooter rider did not stop, and the e-scooter made contact with the right rear tail light of the Zoox vehicle. The e-scooter rider remained upright, did not stop to exchange information, and immediately rode off while the Zoox vehicle was still stopped. There were no injuries and police were not called. The damage to the Zoox vehicle was limited to a cracked tail light lens.

Operating Entity: Mercedes-Benz Research and Development North America
Narrative: The subject Mercedes-Benz vehicle was driving in stop and go traffic on the [XXX] in Gardena, California with the L3 ADS activated. The test route selected by the driver in the vehicle's navigation system indicated an upcoming exit, so the driver began to prepare for a lane change towards the highway exit by deactivating the L3 ADS and activating the turn signal. Once the vehicle was in conventional driving mode, the driver looked for a gap in the adjacent lane to merge towards the exit lane, applied the brakes, and slowed the vehicle down. The SUV following the Mercedes-Benz vehicle did not respond in time to the vehicle's braking and contacted the rear of the Mercedes-Benz approximately 10 seconds after the L3 ADS was deactivated.  The Mercedes-Benz vehicle experienced minor damage to the rear bumper. No injuries were reported, no airbags deployed in either vehicle, and both vehicles were driven from the scene of the incident.

Operating Entity: Mercedes-Benz Research and Development North America
Narrative: Mercedes-Benz has conducted a review of the incident and the following is based on that review. The subject Mercedes-Benz Drive Pilot test vehicle was traveling between 15-20 mph in the #2 northbound lane on the [XXX] in California in stop and go traffic with the L3 ADS activated by the driver. The vehicle's ADS determined that a truck traveling in the adjacent lane had a trajectory towards the Drive Pilot's lane, and so the Mercedes-Benz test vehicle autonomously applied the brakes to avoid a collision. After applying the brakes and bringing itself to a standstill, the Mercedes-Benz was then struck in the rear bumper by a trailing semi-truck that did not stop in time. No injuries were reported, no airbags deployed in either vehicle, and both vehicles were able to be driven from the scene of the incident. The Mercedes-Benz vehicle experienced minor damage to the rear bumper, and no damage was observed on the semi-truck at the scene. The CA Traffic Collision Report for the subject incident noted a violation of California Vehicle Code 22350 (unsafe speed for traffic conditions) by the semi-truck in the #2 lane that struck the rear bumper of the Mercedes-Benz.

On November [XXX], 2022 at 8:48 AM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in Phoenix, Arizona was in a collision involving a garbage truck on the 500 block of [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling eastbound on [XXX] when it encountered a stopped garbage truck traveling westbound. The garbage truck then attempted to pass between the Waymo AV and a parked passenger vehicle to the right of the garbage truck, and the garbage truck made contact with the left rear corner of the Waymo AV. On December [XXX], 2022, a Navya ARMA shuttle operated by Beep (VIN 1N9A1SACXJS[XXX]) was involved in a non-injury collision while operating in manual mode on [XXX] in Port Saint Lucie, FL.  While driving along [XXX] under autonomous control, the shuttle encountered a parked vehicle partially blocking its path, requiring disengagement of the autonomous drive system.  The safety driver attempted to manually drive the shuttle around the parked vehicle to reengage the autonomous drive system.  While manually steering the shuttle around the parked vehicle blocking its path, the shuttle failed to respond to manual control input and steered to the left, impacting a parked vehicle at a low rate of speed on the opposite side of [XXX].  The six passengers onboard alighted the shuttle, an accident report was filed with the local police, and the shuttle was removed from the scene.  Initial reports from the onboard safety driver indicated that while steering around the vehicle blocking the shuttle's path, the shuttle became unresponsive to control input.  The safety driver released the operator present button on the vehicle controller, which serves as dead man switch however, the vehicle failed to stop.  After the incident, further investigation by Navya confirmed that the root cause of the incident was a failure of the Xbox 360 controller used to manually control the vehicle.  Contact with the parked vehicle occurred between the time of failure and the vehicle drive system recognizing that the controller had failed an elapsed time of 4.05 seconds. In response to the incident, Beep suspended operation of all Navya ARMA vehicles pending identification and implementation of appropriate solutions to mitigate the risk of this failure leading to future incidents.
Subsequent investigation by Beep and Navya determined that the vehicle control software, NavyaDrive, is limited in its ability to monitor the validity of control signal input received from the Xbox 360 controller.  As the safety driver began to manually steer the vehicle, the controller failed, sending constant turning input to the vehicle drive system leading to the collision.  Though Navya developed software mitigations due to prior issues encountered with the controller, those mitigations were ineffective with respect to the failure leading to the incident on December [XXX].  Further, due to the short time between the controller failing and the collision (2.34sec), the safety driver was unable to identify the controller failure and trigger the emergency stop before the collision occurred.
In response to the incident, Navya is integrating a revised manual control system on the ARMA shuttle platform.  The revised manual control system utilizes industrial-grade components for improved electromechanical reliability and allows for active monitoring of the control system health, eliminating the root cause of the failure that led to the incident on December [XXX].  Software upgrades of all Navya ARMA vehicles will further reintroduce automated braking function while the ARMA vehicle is under manual control.  Beep is working with Navya to retrofit its fleet of ARMA vehicles with the revised manual control system as well as retrain and recertify its safety driver staff on the updated NavyaDrive software.
Discussion of the root cause analysis and solution design for the revised manual control system will be provided to NHTSA as a supplement to this report.

The initial submission was by email and electronic form to SGO Mailbox on 10/18/2022 at 10:09PM.  This is a resubmission of data using the SGO portal with Volvo Cars USA, LLC account on behalf of Polestar Automotive USA. Volvo Cars USA, LLC is submitting this report on behalf of Polestar Automotive USA and Polestar Performance AB.  The vehicle was a company vehicle (owned by Polestar Automotive USA) driven by a company employee, with no known modifications to the factory hardware condition or software updates or changes not released to the public. Subject vehicle was traveling around a curve on the freeway interchange at approximately 55mph, recommended speed in that portion of exchange was 50mph.  Driver looked down and took attention off the road.  The vehicle continued slightly straight, running up and grazing off the concrete barrier, before coming back into the lane.  The vehicle's rear suspension, rear and front wheel/tire were damaged. Vehicle was towed from the scene. We have recovered data from the vehicle and are currently reviewing what information was stored for the incident and will update this report.
10 Day update: After review of the EDR data the technical team was able to determine the following: Pilot Assist was disengaged due to the lateral acceleration exceeded the system limit and the available steering torque system input exceeding the limit.  The vehicle could not steer enough to follow the lane. Several warnings were issued: visually in the DIM (Drivers Information Module, display), haptically in the steering wheel, before Pilot Assist was disengaged. The driver is always responsible for ensuring that the vehicle is driven in a safe manner. The driver failed to take control of the vehicle when the vehicles Pilot Assist gave the warnings.

On Aug [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION], 2022 at [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION] CST a Kodiak Autonomous Vehicle ("Kodiak AV") Class 8 semi-truck driving southbound on [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION] in [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION] Texas was rear-ended by a pickup truck. The Kodiak AV had been braking for over 11 seconds in lane to safely accommodate two pedestrians and their vehicles near the fog line on the shoulder when a pickup truck rear-ended the Kodiak AV. 
The Kodiak AV was operating with a safety driver (in the driver's seating position), who transitioned the vehicle from autonomous to manual mode immediately prior to impact. At the time of impact, the Kodiak AV was in manual mode.

Kodiak is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of the Standing General Order 2021-01 because the Kodiak AV was slowing down for vulnerable road users when it was rear-ended. Kodiak may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

A Zoox vehicle in autonomy had made a right turn from [XXX]. onto [XXX]. in Menlo Park, CA and was preparing to make an immediate, unprotected left turn onto [XXX]. On June [XXX], 2022 at approximately 4:50 PM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in San Francisco, California allegedly contributed to a collision between a passenger vehicle and a pickup truck on [XXX] at [XXX], according to a claim by the driver of the passenger vehicle.
The Waymo AV was in autonomous mode and preparing to enter southbound [XXX] as a passenger vehicle on [XXX] approached from behind.  A pickup truck was traveling next to the passenger vehicle in the adjacent left lane.  As the passenger vehicle approached the Waymo AV from behind, the passenger vehicle entered the adjacent left lane that was occupied by the pickup truck and maneuvered around the Waymo AV.  The pickup truck proceeded without stopping, and the passenger vehicle's driver shortly after signaled to the Waymo AV test driver to pull over.  The Waymo AV test driver then transitioned to manual mode and pulled over.  Transdev has no data or knowledge of any contact between any of the three vehicles.  There was no contact or collision between the Waymo AV and any other vehicle.  However, the driver and passenger in the passenger vehicle have subsequently alleged injuries based on alleged contact between the pick-up truck and passenger vehicle, which contact their allegations attribute to the behavior of Waymo's AV in a bodily injury claim under Waymo's insurance policy.  Waymo received notice of this insurance claim on July [XXX].
Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this event under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01.  Transdev may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.  This report is a duplicate of 30270-3655-1.

Subject vehicle was on a testing mission in Mountain View, CA.  The vehicle was traveling North-bound on [XXX] operated by the vehicle's Level 4 Automated Driving System and supervised by a safety driver in the driver's designated seating position, and with a safety operator in the front passenger seating position.  Subject vehicle approached a red light to make a right turn East-bound onto [XXX].  The safety operator suggested that the safety driver disengage the ADS and make the turn in manual mode because the vehicle was hesitant in approaching the intersection. The safety driver disengaged the ADS, and, approximately 250ms later, subject vehicle was lightly struck from behind by a white Mazda3.  Having seen debris on the roadway, the driver and operator believed they had run over a rock and did not realize they were hit by the vehicle. After concluding the mission, the driver and operator found damage to a sensor during an inspection.  A subsequent review of video led to discovery of the crash.  No injuries were reported, and law enforcement was not called to the scene.  
In addition to telematics and video, we also have photographs of the vehicle's damaged sensor.

All of the data in this report and the following text is an excerpt from TuSimples original submission (30370-2949-1) and constitutes Navistars sole understanding of this event.
TuSimple's position is that this event does not meet the criteria for reporting under the SGO.
Specifically, the L4 ADS was not in operation at any point in the 30 seconds prior to making contact with the concrete barrier.
The event occurred as follows:
As the truck was being operated on the highway, within its mapped ODD, the driver and test engineer attempted to engage the ADS.
However, the ADS was not functional at that moment due to the computer unit not having been initialized, and should not have been
attempted to be activated. In short, this was a failed attempt to engage the system as a result of human error.
The system has now been modified to prevent the ADS from attempting to engage unless the health of the system is fully functional to
prevent human error from repeating this event.
When the erroneous attempt to engage occurred, the uninitialized vehicle control unit rotated the steering to the left, causing the truck to
veer left. The safety driver took control of the steering, and was able to steer accordingly, but not before the left front truck tire and left
front quarter panel came into contact with the concrete barrier to the left of the lanes of travel.

The Beep shuttle attendant was traveling Southbound on [XXX] at approx 7-12 mph in ADS and headed towards the intersection of [XXX]. Beep vehicle stopped at red light at intersection. As the Beep vehicle was crossing the intersection in manual and slowing to a stop to return to ADS in a southbound direction, the trailing bus made light contact with its bicycle rack to the Beep shuttle rear end. The trailing vehicle is a bus owned and operated by the Pinellas Suncoast Transit Authority (PSTA). According to video, as reported by the shuttle attendant and the PSTA Road Supervisor, the bus was tailgating. 
 
Root Cause: Trailing vehicle following too closely and not observing Navya slowing to a stop.

The May vehicle was traveling on an unpainted (no center line) residential road with vehicles parked along the right side of the road. The May vehicle passed too close to a parked vehicle, causing the May vehicle's passenger-side mirror to contact the parked vehicle's driver-side mirror.
The May vehicle's ground mapping module had fallen significantly behind in its processing of lidar data. As a result, actual objects were being filtered out of the lidar data during object detection. This filtering caused the truck to oscillate between being detected, detecting only the cab, detecting the cab and mirror, and not being detected at all.
After assessing the issue, it has been determined that ground map latency alone will not cause safety issues. There is no risk to VRUs, or anything at ground level. The issue was with something in the air (mirror), above the ground.
A permanent fix to address the ground map latency issue is in process and will be implemented in the entire fleet within the next 30 days.
The second factor in the collision is that we were artificially constraining the vehicle to the right side of the road due to ambiguous and unpainted roadway. If we change that constraint to an advisory line (and allow the vehicle to cross the line to the left), we would have been far enough to the left to avoid collision (simulation success).
Solution Implementation: AVO training for extra caution related to protruding items like mirrors (short term), software changes coming in the next update and hotfix (within 30 days), and further improvement in the following update (within 60 days).
Until the tested software changes are implemented, we have advised the AVOs to take extra caution in these scenarios and to continue to disengage autonomy when desired. As always, we sacrifice autonomy for safety, as needed.

TuSimple's position is that this event does not meet the criteria for reporting under the SGO.
Specifically, the L4 ADS was not in operation at any point in the 30 seconds prior to making contact with the concrete barrier.  
 
The event occurred as follows:
As the truck was being operated on the highway, within its mapped ODD, the driver and test engineer attempted to engage the ADS.  However, the ADS was not functional at that moment due to the computer unit not having been initialized, and should not have been attempted to be activated.  In short, this was a failed attempt to engage the system as a result of human error.  
 
The system has now been modified to prevent the ADS from attempting to engage unless the health of the system is fully functional to prevent human error from repeating this event.
 
When the erroneous attempt to engage occurred, the uninitialized vehicle control unit rotated the steering to the left, causing the truck to veer left.  The safety driver took control of the steering, and was able to steer accordingly, but not before the left front truck tire and left front quarter panel came into contact with the concrete barrier to the left of the lanes of travel.  
 
The contact resulted in a scuff to the left tire and damage to the radar unit extending from the left quarter panel.

UNEDITED NARRATIVE FROM ORIGINAL MONTHLY REPORT (11/[XXX]/21) AND AMENDED REPORT (11/[XXX]/21): On October [XXX], 2021, after turning right onto [XXX] from [XXX], the Pony.ai Autonomous Vehicle ("Pony.ai AV") performed a left lane change maneuver in autonomous mode (SAE L4). While performing the lane change, the Pony.ai AV came into contact with a center divider on [XXX]. and the traffic sign that was posted on the divider. On November [XXX], 2021 at 8:02 PM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ('Waymo AV') operating in San Francisco, CA was in a collision involving a passenger vehicle at [XXX], [XXX], and [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was traveling southbound on [XXX], a narrow road with vehicles parked on both sides, and approaching the intersection with [XXX] and [XXX]. A passenger vehicle approaching from the right of the Waymo AV on eastbound [XXX] made a left turn in front of the Waymo AV to head northbound on [XXX]. The Waymo AV slowed to a near stop and nudged to its right in order to share the narrow road with the oncoming vehicle and then came to a stop at the stop sign as the oncoming vehicle completed its turn. At approximately 5 mph, the turning passenger vehicle made contact with Waymo AV's sensor hardware housing on the driver side rear corner fender of the stopped Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present (in the driver's seating position). The Waymo AV sustained minor damage to the sensor hardware housing (which was the reason for towing the Waymo AV) and the passenger vehicle left the scene without exchanging information.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vehicle involved was towed away. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

A Local Motors electric Olli shuttle (V1.0), VIN equipped with the Robotic Research autonomy kit (enabling autonomous steering, acceleration, deceleration, and braking (AutoDrive)), was proceeding forward in autonomous mode through a parking lot in Yellowstone National Park.
